---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Microbiome Transformers | Quintin Pope">
  <div class="project-header">
    <a href="/projects" class="back-link">&larr; Projects</a>
    <h1>Learning a Deep Language Model for Microbiomes</h1>
    <p class="project-desc">
      Adapting NLP self-supervised pretraining to gut microbiome data. We used an ELECTRA-style
      transformer to learn context-sensitive taxa embeddings from the American Gut Project, producing
      representations that capture taxonomic structure, correlate with metabolic pathways, and
      generalize to independent disease-prediction datasets. Published in
      <a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pcbi.1011353" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PLOS Computational Biology, 2025</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="project-authors">
      Quintin Pope, Rohan Varma, Christine Tataru, Maude M. David, Xiaoli Fern
    </p>
    <div class="project-links-row">
      <a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pcbi.1011353" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Paper &rarr;</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/QuintinPope/microbiome_transformers" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub &rarr;</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Motivation -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Motivation</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        The human gut microbiome&mdash;the ecosystem of trillions of microbes living in our digestive
        tract&mdash;is linked to conditions ranging from inflammatory bowel disease to mental health.
        But microbiome datasets are high-dimensional, sparse, and notoriously variable across studies.
        Standard machine learning models trained on one cohort often fail on another.
      </p>
      <p>
        We asked: can the same self-supervised pretraining revolution that transformed NLP also work
        for microbial communities? By treating each microbiome sample as a "sentence" of microbial
        taxa ranked by abundance, we trained a transformer to learn the compositional grammar of
        microbial ecosystems from large-scale unlabeled data.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Approach -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Approach</h2>
    <div class="figure-img overview-diagram">
      <img src="/images/microbiome/Embedding_production_diagram_Fig_1.png" alt="Overview of the microbiome transformer pipeline: input samples are preprocessed into ranked taxa sequences, fed through a pretrained transformer, and used for both sample-level prediction and context-sensitive taxa embeddings." />
      <p class="figure-caption">Fig 1. End-to-end pipeline: microbiome samples are converted to ranked taxa sequences, processed by a pretrained transformer, and used for sample classification (via CLS token) and context-sensitive taxa embeddings.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pipeline">
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <div class="step-number">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Tokenization</h3>
          <p>
            Each microbiome sample is converted to a token sequence by ranking all observed taxa in
            decreasing order of relative abundance, truncated to the 512 most abundant&mdash;analogous
            to words in a sentence.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <div class="step-number">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>ELECTRA Pretraining</h3>
          <p>
            A generator network learns to predict masked taxa from the surrounding microbial context.
            A discriminator network then learns to distinguish generator-filled taxa from original ones.
            Both share a transformer backbone trained on unlabeled American Gut Project data.
          </p>
          <div class="step-figure">
            <img src="/images/microbiome/Pretraining_diagram_Fig_3.png" alt="ELECTRA pretraining scheme showing generator and discriminator transformer architecture" />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <div class="step-number">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Finetuning</h3>
          <p>
            The pretrained discriminator's token-level head is replaced with a CLS classification head.
            Labeled microbiome data is then used to finetune for downstream tasks such as IBD prediction
            and dietary pattern classification.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Key Results -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Key Results</h2>
    <div class="results-grid">
      <div class="card result-card">
        <h3>Cross-Study Generalization</h3>
        <p>
          While in-domain performance on IBD and diet prediction was comparable to baselines, the
          transformer representations <strong>significantly outperformed</strong> all baselines
          when generalizing to independent test datasets (Halfvarson, HMP2)&mdash;even under
          substantial distribution shift between training and test populations.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card result-card">
        <h3>Context-Sensitive Embeddings</h3>
        <p>
          Unlike static embeddings (e.g., GloVe), the transformer produces
          <strong>contextualized representations</strong> where the same bacterial taxon receives
          different embeddings depending on its microbial neighbors. This mirrors how the same word
          means different things in different sentences.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card result-card">
        <h3>Emergent Biological Structure</h3>
        <p>
          Despite never being given taxonomic labels, the pretrained embeddings spontaneously
          organized by phylum. K-means clustering on contextualized embeddings achieved roughly
          <strong>20 percentage points higher phylum purity</strong> compared to GloVe-style
          embeddings.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card result-card">
        <h3>Metabolic Pathway Correlations</h3>
        <p>
          Embedding dimensions showed statistically significant correlations with known metabolic
          pathways, despite the model never being exposed to metabolic data. The contextualized
          embeddings captured <strong>stronger pathway correlations</strong> than prior embedding
          methods.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Visual Highlights -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Visual Highlights from the Paper</h2>

    <div class="figure-card">
      <div class="figure-header">
        <span class="figure-label">Fig 4</span>
        <h3>Taxonomic Structure Emerges in Embedding Space</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="figure-img">
        <img src="/images/microbiome/Phylum_colored_embeddings_Fig_4.png" alt="t-SNE visualizations of vocabulary embeddings (a) vs contextualized embeddings (b) colored by phylum, with phylum purity comparison plot (c)" />
      </div>
      <div class="figure-description">
        <p>
          t-SNE visualizations comparing original vocabulary embeddings (left) with contextualized
          transformer embeddings (right), each point colored by phylum. The vocabulary embeddings
          show some phylum clustering, but the contextualized embeddings form dramatically tighter,
          more distinct phylum groups. A companion plot of phylum purity vs. number of K-means
          clusters confirms this quantitatively: the transformer's contextualized space consistently
          achieves ~20 percentage points higher purity across all values of K.
        </p>
        <p class="figure-takeaway">
          The transformer learns that taxonomically related bacteria behave similarly&mdash;without
          ever being told which bacteria are related.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-card">
      <div class="figure-header">
        <span class="figure-label">Fig 5</span>
        <h3>Contextualization Disentangles Mixed Clusters</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="figure-img">
        <img src="/images/microbiome/Embeddings_comparisons_Fig_5.png" alt="Mapping between vocabulary and contextualized embedding spaces showing how taxa from mixed clusters get reorganized into coherent phylum groups" />
      </div>
      <div class="figure-description">
        <p>
          This figure maps how taxa move between the vocabulary embedding space and the
          contextualized embedding space. Taxa from a single phylum that were scattered across
          multiple clusters in the vocabulary space get pulled into tight, coherent clusters after
          contextualization. The transformer extracts "threads" of related taxa from mixed
          neighborhoods and reorganizes them by biological function.
        </p>
        <p class="figure-takeaway">
          Context transforms a noisy embedding into one where biological relationships become the
          dominant organizational principle.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-card">
      <div class="figure-header">
        <span class="figure-label">Fig 7</span>
        <h3>Metabolic Pathway Correlations</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="figure-img">
        <img src="/images/microbiome/Correlation_strength_histograms_Fig_7.png" alt="Histogram comparing correlation strength distributions between contextualized transformer embeddings and GloVe embeddings against metabolic pathways" />
      </div>
      <div class="figure-description">
        <p>
          Distribution of the magnitude of statistically significant correlations between embedding
          dimensions and known metabolic pathways, comparing the contextualized transformer
          embeddings against prior GloVe-based microbiome embeddings. The transformer embeddings
          exhibit stronger correlations with metabolic function, suggesting the model captures
          functionally relevant microbial interactions during pretraining.
        </p>
        <p class="figure-takeaway">
          Self-supervised pretraining on abundance data alone recovers signals about microbial
          metabolism.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-card">
      <div class="figure-header">
        <span class="figure-label">Fig 8</span>
        <h3>IBD Attribution in Embedding Space</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="figure-img">
        <img src="/images/microbiome/Attribution_colored_contextual_embeddings_Fig_8.png" alt="t-SNE visualization of contextualized embeddings colored by IBD attribution, with warm yellow for IBD-associated taxa and deep purple for healthy-associated taxa" />
      </div>
      <div class="figure-description">
        <p>
          A t-SNE visualization of the contextualized embeddings colored by attribution to
          inflammatory bowel disease (IBD). Taxa associated with IBD appear in warm yellow tones,
          while taxa associated with healthy states appear in deep purple. The separation reveals that
          the pretrained representations already encode disease-relevant structure before any
          supervised finetuning on IBD labels.
        </p>
        <p class="figure-takeaway">
          Disease signal is latent in the microbial language&mdash;the transformer learns to surface it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- About -->
  <section class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">About the Approach</h2>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Why ELECTRA?</h3>
        <p>
          ELECTRA's replaced-token-detection objective is more sample-efficient than masked language
          modeling (BERT-style), which matters when working with biological datasets far smaller than
          typical NLP corpora. The discriminator sees every token rather than just the ~15% that are
          masked, extracting more training signal per sample.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Data: American Gut Project</h3>
        <p>
          The model was pretrained on 16S rRNA amplicon sequencing data from the American Gut
          Project&mdash;one of the largest crowd-sourced microbiome studies. This provided a broad
          base of microbial community diversity for learning general-purpose representations.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Generalization Challenge</h3>
        <p>
          Microbiome data varies enormously across studies due to differences in sample collection,
          DNA extraction, sequencing protocols, and study populations. Models that perform well
          in-domain often collapse on external data. Our cross-study evaluation directly measures
          this critical capability.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .project-header {
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .project-desc {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    max-width: 760px;
  }

  .project-authors {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .project-links-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.2rem;
    margin-top: 0.8rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .prose {
    max-width: 760px;
  }

  .prose p {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  /* Pipeline steps */
  .pipeline {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1rem;
    max-width: 760px;
  }

  .pipeline-step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.2rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
    background: var(--color-bg-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1.2rem 1.5rem;
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }

  .pipeline-step:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .step-number {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 32px;
    height: 32px;
    background: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-bg);
    border-radius: 50%;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  .step-content h3 {
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-bottom: 0.3rem;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
  }

  .step-content p {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  /* Results grid */
  .results-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  .result-card h3 {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .result-card p {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  /* Figure cards */
  .figure-card {
    background: var(--color-bg-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }

  .figure-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .figure-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.8rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.8rem;
  }

  .figure-label {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    background: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-bg);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
  }

  .figure-header h3 {
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
  }

  .figure-description p {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }

  /* Figure images */
  .figure-img {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .figure-img img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 6px;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    background: #fff;
    padding: 0.75rem;
  }

  .figure-caption {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .overview-diagram {
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .overview-diagram img {
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .step-figure {
    margin-top: 0.8rem;
  }

  .step-figure img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 4px;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    background: #fff;
    padding: 0.5rem;
  }

  .figure-takeaway {
    color: var(--color-accent) !important;
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 0.88rem !important;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    padding-left: 0.8rem;
    margin-top: 0.4rem;
  }

  /* Info grid */
  .info-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  .info-grid .card h3 {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .info-grid .card p {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .results-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
